title: Hot Chocolate
json_data:
{"type": "food", "name": "Hot Chocolate", "summary": "

This Hot Chocolate Recipe was prepared and served by Mary Jo McFadden when she entertained the Brunkhorst/McFadden families at Christmas. This recipe was submitted by several family members with notes attached how each would look forward to this awesome treat each year! (Note: Mary Jo is known for always typing instead of writing. She was also noted for calling her children and siblings in the morning to wish them a \"good day!\" Mary Jo is sadly missed by all who knew her.)

", "author_display": "enabled", "author_name": "Mary Jo McFadden", "ingredients_flat": [{"amount": "1", "unit": "cup", "name": "sugar", "notes": "", "type": "ingredient"}, {"amount": "1", "unit": "cup", "name": "cocoa", "notes": "", "type": "ingredient"}, {"amount": "1", "unit": "cup", "name": "water", "notes": "boiling", "type": "ingredient"}, {"amount": "1", "unit": "quart", "name": "heavy cream", "notes": "", "type": "ingredient"}, {"amount": "4", "unit": "quarts", "name": "milk", "notes": "scalding hot", "type": "ingredient"}], "instructions_flat": [{"text": "

Mix sugar and cocoa, stir to a smooth paste with the boiling water. Heat over the direct flame and then cook in a double boiler for about 30 minutes, or until a thick paste is formed. Chill.

", "type": "instruction", "image_url": ""}, {"text": "

Whip cream. Fold in cocoa paste, scald milk in double boiler or pan, add vanilla and salt. When serving hot chocolate, put chocolate mixture in a bowl and hot milk in a pitcher. Put a large spoonful of chocolate mixture in cup: add hot milk. Be sure milk is scalding hot; otherwise beverage will be lukewarm because of the cold paste that is added. I put sugar with my whipping cream when I whip it and some vanilla too.

", "type": "instruction", "image_url": ""}]}
author: Mary Jo McFadden
summary: This Hot Chocolate Recipe was prepared and served by Mary Jo McFadden when she entertained the Brunkhorst/McFadden families at Christmas. This recipe was submitted by several family members with notes attached how each would look forward to this awesome treat each year! (Note: Mary Jo is known for always typing instead of writing. She was also noted for calling her children and siblings in the morning to wish them a "good day!" Mary Jo is sadly missed by all who knew her.)
instructions:
[{'text': '

Mix sugar and cocoa, stir to a smooth paste with the boiling water. Heat over the direct flame and then cook in a double boiler for about 30 minutes, or until a thick paste is formed. Chill.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Whip cream. Fold in cocoa paste, scald milk in double boiler or pan, add vanilla and salt. When serving hot chocolate, put chocolate mixture in a bowl and hot milk in a pitcher. Put a large spoonful of chocolate mixture in cup: add hot milk. Be sure milk is scalding hot; otherwise beverage will be lukewarm because of the cold paste that is added. I put sugar with my whipping cream when I whip it and some vanilla too.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}]

title: Dandelion Wine
json_data:
{"type": "food", "name": "Dandelion Wine", "summary": "

This recipe was a recipe of Grandma Anna Brunkhorst, submitted by granddaughter, Ann Fabric, daughter of Della Wintakger.

Note received by Vivian Shane, daughter of Della and sister to Ann: I used to

stay during high school years with Grandma Brunkhorst in her home in

Lamont, Iowa. This was only on nights when I had special practice. At our

evening meal, Grandma served me a small glass of her homemade dandelion

wine. Since I was a teenager and had not drank wine I was very frustrated as

to whether I should drink it or not. Finally, I rationalized Anna was my

mother's mother so she wouldn't serve me anything I shouldn't have. I drank

the wine!

", "author_display": "enabled", "author_name": "Ann Fabric", "ingredients_flat": [{"amount": "4", "unit": "gallons", "name": "dandelion flowers", "notes": "", "type": "ingredient"}, {"amount": "4", "unit": "gallons", "name": "water", "notes": "boiling", "type": "ingredient"}, {"amount": "4", "unit": "lb", "name": "honey", "notes": "", "type": "ingredient"}, {"amount": "4", "unit": "", "name": "lemons", "notes": "sliced", "type": "ingredient"}, {"amount": "4", "unit": "", "name": "oranges", "notes": "sliced", "type": "ingredient"}, {"amount": "12", "unit": "", "name": "whole cloves", "notes": "", "type": "ingredient"}, {"amount": "2", "unit": "tbsp", "name": "yeast", "notes": "2 packages", "type": "ingredient"}, {"amount": "\u00bd", "unit": "cup", "name": "water", "notes": "warm", "type": "ingredient"}], "instructions_flat": [{"text": "

Remove any stems from the flowers. Put the flowers in a large, warm crock and pour the boiling water over them. Let stand for a week.

", "type": "instruction", "image_url": ""}, {"text": "

Strain, squeezing all the juice out of the flowers; then discard. Add the slices of lemon, orange and the cloves; stir well. Add the yeast which has been softened in the warm water. Let stand, covered for another 2 weeks.

", "type": "instruction", "image_url": ""}, {"text": "

Strain again and pour into wine bottles. Let the bottles stand uncorked for 5 days. Cork or cap bottles. Let wine develop for at least 2 months.

", "type": "instruction", "image_url": ""}]}
author: Ann Fabric
summary:
This recipe was a recipe of Grandma Anna Brunkhorst, submitted by granddaughter, Ann Fabric, daughter of Della Wintakger.

Note received by Vivian Shane, daughter of Della and sister to Ann: I used to

stay during high school years with Grandma Brunkhorst in her home in

Lamont, Iowa. This was only on nights when I had special practice. At our

evening meal, Grandma served me a small glass of her homemade dandelion

wine. Since I was a teenager and had not drank wine I was very frustrated as

to whether I should drink it or not. Finally, I rationalized Anna was my

mother's mother so she wouldn't serve me anything I shouldn't have. I drank

the wine!
instructions:
[{'text': '

Remove any stems from the flowers. Put the flowers in a large, warm crock and pour the boiling water over them. Let stand for a week.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Strain, squeezing all the juice out of the flowers; then discard. Add the slices of lemon, orange and the cloves; stir well. Add the yeast which has been softened in the warm water. Let stand, covered for another 2 weeks.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Strain again and pour into wine bottles. Let the bottles stand uncorked for 5 days. Cork or cap bottles. Let wine develop for at least 2 months.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}]
